## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns from the skill guide:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join(timeout)` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it no longer exists. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The runtime will not forcibly terminate a thread; you must use **cooperative cancellation**.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` is long-running and must actually stop

The above only abandons the task — it doesn't stop `work()`. For true cooperative cancellation, change the signature to accept a token:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller example:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the token only works at checkpoints. If `work()` never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It holds timer resources. Always `using` it. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Uncooperative code can't be stopped** | If you call a blocking API you don't control (e.g., native call), move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill`. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. |
| **`Task.Run` uses the thread pool** | Unlike the original explicit `new Thread()`. If you need a dedicated thread (e.g., STA), use `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`. |

### What Was Removed

| Removed API | Replacement |
|-------------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` (automatic via timeout) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Not needed — check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
